{"key":"post-12300659","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12300659</id>\n<content>First of all, hydrometers measure the specific gravity of liquids.&amp;nbsp; There is no use for one in mycology.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, while 100% humidity is fine, it's worthless without massive air exchange.&amp;nbsp; Fresh air is the pinning trigger you want, not saturation humidity.&amp;nbsp; Your idea of a paper towel test won't tell anything.&amp;nbsp; If you want a terrarium for fruiting small bulk substrates, build a shotgun terrarium.&amp;nbsp; It's about the best way to go if you don't have a hygrometer.&amp;nbsp; If you build it &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;per the tek,&lt;/a&gt; your humidity will be correct.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12300624</prev>\n<first>12300597</first>\n<last>12300659</last>\n<when>1269989712</when>\n<utime>03/31/10 01:55 AM</utime>\n</post>"}